<br>
Most good songs are BUILT on the bedrock of the rhythm (sp?  one word I can never get right) section.  Just because they don't have the flash or the panache of the lead singer / axeman guitarist doesn't mean a damn thing.  <br>
<br>
The quinessential example of this is Led Zeppelin.  Take away the &quot;image&quot; of Jimmy Page and Robert Plant, and judge them on the individual importance to each song, and you see that the heart and soul of that band is - at least in my mind, and I'll throw rocks at anybody who argues - is the deadly (and partly dead) duo of John Paul Jones and John Bonham.<br>
<br>
But you are right, most drummers and bassists are unable to capitalize and move on to solo careers... Sting, Dave Grohl, Paul McCartney, Phil Collins, and (arguably, since his &quot;solo&quot; career is merely him transcending the rest of the band) Les Claypool are the exceptions that prove the rule.<br>
<br>
But you know what?  I've HEARD the solo work of guys like Joe Satriani, Robert Plant, that other guy that sounds like Joe Satriani, and countless others... you can be the best singer or guitarist in the world, but you sound like crap unless you have the right guys laying the beat for you, irrespective of genre, style, or period.<br>
<br>
*nod*  <br>
<br>
Please note that Uinin's percussion skill is always the first to max out, and you'll never see me do anything important with a double-necked heart-shaped lute.<br>
